{"type":"message","id":"90deceac","parentId":"d48b0d9c","timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:26:29.345Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The dist/client/ only has `.assetsignore` and `assets/` - no index.html. TanStack Start generates the HTML shell server-side, so there's no static index.html. The client build is just the JS/CSS chunks.\n\nThis means we can't simply copy these files to replace the control UI. The cockpit is fundamentally an SSR application that needs a server.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The user wants to \"replace the control ui with design and theming from the ui\". Since we can't easily make the cockpit a static replacement for the control UI, we have a few options:\n\n1. **Run the cockpit as a separate app** - Serve it on a different port and access it there\n2. **Extract the design system** - Take the CSS variables and colors from the cockpit and create a theme for the Control UI\n3. **Proxy/integrate** - Set up the OpenClaw gateway to proxy to the cockpit app\n\nFor option 1, we can use `bun run preview` or `bun run dev` to serve the cockpit. But this requires the server to be running.\n\nFor option 2, the Control UI supports tweakcn themes. We could extract the cockpit's CSS and create a compatible theme.\n\nFor option 3, we could potentially configure a reverse proxy.\n\nActually, wait - let me re-read the TanStack Start docs. Maybe there's a way to generate a static site. Some frameworks have `prerender` options.\n\nBut also, I should think about what the user ACTUALLY wants. They said \"replace the control ui with design and theming from the ui\". Maybe they don't need the full cockpit app to replace the control UI - they just want the LOOK AND FEEL (design and theming) applied.\n\nThe cockpit has a very specific dark aesthetic:\n- Background: `oklch(0.04 0.01 260)` (very dark blue-black)\n- Foreground: `oklch(0.97 0.005 250)` (almost white)\n- Card backgrounds with low opacity white overlays (`bg-white/[0.06]`, etc.)\n- Rounded-full buttons and inputs\n- Clean, minimal design\n\nThe Control UI (based on docs) supports theme imports from tweakcn. If I can create a tweakcn-compatible theme from the cockpit's design tokens, the user can import it into the Control UI's Appearance panel.\n\nLet me check if there's a way to create a tweakcn theme file. Actually, looking at the docs, tweakcn themes are registry URLs or editor URLs. The format is likely JSON with color variables.\n\nBut I'm not sure about the exact tweakcn theme format. Let me check if the cockpit has any theme-related exports or if there's a way to extract the CSS variables into a theme format.\n\nActually, let me focus on a more practical approach. Since the cockpit built successfully, let me:\n1. Try running the dev server or preview server\n2. Also extract the design tokens into a reusable theme file\n3. Update the workspace to document how to use the cockpit\n\nFor the \"replace control UI\" part - since the control UI is a built-in OpenClaw feature and the cockpit is a separate app, the most practical integration is to run the cockpit alongside and potentially proxy it.\n\nBut wait, looking at the output more carefully, the client build DOES have an index.html generated by the SSR build. Let me check if there's one in dist/server or if we can generate a static version.\n\nActually, I realize I should check if there's a `.vite/manifest.json` that might reference an HTML entry point. Or maybe I need to use a different build command for static generation.\n\nLet me check if TanStack Start has a static build option.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tool_kuNFB8BBwSpRU5j8RfX82vKw","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/Users/asherlewis/.openclaw/workspace/openclaw-cockpit/dist/server/.vite/manifest.json"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"kimi","model":"kimi-for-coding","usage":{"input":227,"output":809,"cacheRead":57856,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":58892,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1779391568156,"responseId":"msg_ys9y3k6baFjJZiInBQOHR9pQ"}}
