{"type":"message","id":"3d16b1bb","parentId":"bef66c05","timestamp":"2026-05-21T19:27:47.995Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The wrangler.jsonc points to `src/server.ts` as the main entry. The build output is `dist/server/index.js` because the Cloudflare/vite plugin uses `index.js` as the default output name.\n\nInstead of trying to hack the build output, let me take a different approach. Since the prerendering needs `server.js`, I can:\n1. Add a post-build script to copy `index.js` to `server.js`\n2. Or just manually run the prerender step\n\nActually, let me check if there's a way to run just the prerender step. But that's complicated.\n\nLet me take a step back. The user's main goal is to \"replace the control ui with design and theming from the ui\". The prerendering approach was an attempt to generate static files. But maybe there's a simpler way.\n\nWhat if I:\n1. Keep the cockpit as a runnable app in the workspace\n2. Set up a script to run it on a specific port\n3. Extract the design tokens into a theme file that can be imported into the Control UI\n4. Document how to use both\n\nOr, even simpler: just extract the cockpit's CSS variables and create a custom theme file for the Control UI. The Control UI already supports theme imports.\n\nBut wait - the Control UI's theme import is browser-local (per the docs: \"Imported themes are stored only in the current browser profile\"). So we'd need to import it manually in each browser.\n\nLet me think about the most practical deliverable:\n1. The cockpit project is already in the workspace and builds successfully\n2. It can be run with `bun run dev` or `bun run preview`\n3. We should document this in TOOLS.md\n4. We can also extract the design system for reference\n\nFor \"replacing the control UI\" - since the control UI is built into OpenClaw and can't be easily replaced without modifying the npm package, the practical approach is to either:\na) Serve the cockpit alongside and access it separately\nb) Extract the theme and import it into the Control UI\n\nLet me check if there's actually a way to replace the control UI files. We COULD overwrite the files in `node_modules/openclaw/dist/control-ui/` but that's not persistent.\n\nActually, I just realized - maybe I can create a wrapper. The OpenClaw control UI is at `~/.openclaw/extensions/kimi-claw/node_modules/openclaw/dist/control-ui/`. If I replace those files with the cockpit's build output, it would work until the next npm install.\n\nBut the cockpit doesn't produce an `index.html` in the client build because it's SSR. We'd need the prerendered HTML.\n\nLet me try a different approach: instead of using TanStack Start's prerendering (which is having issues), let me manually create a static `index.html` that loads the cockpit's client assets. This would be a simple HTML shell that mounts the React app.\n\nActually, looking at TanStack Start more carefully - the `__root.tsx` defines the HTML shell with `RootShell` and `RootComponent`. For a static version, I'd need to render this to HTML.\n\nLet me try yet another approach. Since the prerendering step failed, maybe I can use a Node script to render the app to static HTML using ReactDOMServer.\n\nBut this is getting too complex. Let me simplify.\n\nThe user wants the cockpit integrated. Let me:\n1. Make sure the cockpit builds and runs\n2. Set up a convenient way to start it\n3. Extract the design tokens\n4. Update workspace docs\n\nFor \"replacing the control UI\", I'll document that the cockpit can be accessed at its own port and serves as the workspace's primary UI.\n\nLet me also try to get the prerendering working. The issue was just the missing `server.js`. Let me rebuild and immediately copy the file, then run prerender separately... or just modify the build output.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tool_lxyq2Zp01oo0XbjDT6YrvBZI","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"import { defineConfig } from \"@lovable.dev/v